Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Jórvík, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1440–6 September 1483":"1440–6 september 1483","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1437–1530":"1437–1530","1472–1521":"1472–1521","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","Sept 6, 1483":"6 september 1483","1521":"1521","1530":"1530","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6 september 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30 april 1463","June 1472":"juni 1472","Honeychurch, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1440–6 September 1483":"1440–6 September 1483","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1437–1530":"1437–1530","1472–1521":"1472–1521","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","Sept 6, 1483":"6 September 1483","1521":"1521","1530":"1530","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6 September 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30 April 1463","June 1472":"June 1472","Honeychurch, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Weeks","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Wicks  .","Americanized form of Norwegian and Swedish   Vik  .","History: This surname was brought to North America independently by several different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One of the earliest on record is Leonard Weeks, who emigrated from Somerset, England, to Portsmouth, NH, some time before 1656. — William Weeks, recorded in Edgartown, Martha's Vineyard, MA, from 1653 onward, was probably a cousin or other relative of the John Wickes mentioned at   Wickes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wicks","meanings":["English (southern England and East Anglia): generally a variant of   Wick  ,   Wyke  , or the obsolete form <b>Week</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Occasionally from the plural form of Middle English <i>wik(e)</i>, late Middle English <i>weke</i> ‘building, especially one where dairy products are made’ (compare   Wick  ). An alternative Middle English plural form occurs in   Wicken  ."]},{"name":"Weekes","meanings":["English: variant of   Weeks   or   Wicks  . This form of the surname is frequent in Barbados."]},{"name":"Vik","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Alf, Erik, Lars, Lennart, Nels, Nils.","Norwegian and Swedish: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads all over Norway and Sweden, so named with Old Norse <i>vík</i> ‘small bay, inlet’. In Swedish it may also be a topographic or ornamental name. Compare   Weeks  .","Czech: from a short form of the personal name <i>Viktor</i> (see   Victor  )."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Simon  , now rare, but more common in the Middle Ages, when it gave rise to the surnames <i>Simms</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Weeks was born in 1440, in Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William WEEKES, was 15 and his mother, Jane Prideaux, was 16. He married Lady Alice Kelly Carey on 30 April 1463, in Honeychurch, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 6 September 1483, in Bengeworth, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1440–6 September 1483":"1440–6. september 1483","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1437–1530":"1437–1530","1472–1521":"1472–1521","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","Sept 6, 1483":"6. september 1483","1521":"1521","1530":"1530","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6. september 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30. aprill 1463","June 1472":"juuni 1472","Honeychurch, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1440–6 September 1483":"1440–6. syyskuuta 1483","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1437–1530":"1437–1530","1472–1521":"1472–1521","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","Sept 6, 1483":"6. syyskuuta 1483","1521":"1521","1530":"1530","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6. syyskuuta 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30. huhtikuuta 1463","June 1472":"kesäkuu 1472","Honeychurch, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England"